attributes.description:
Mid-year population estimates: Scotland and Renfrewshire by single year of age and sex 1981 to 2018.

Annual publication of mid-year population estimates by age and sex as at 30 June every year, where population for higher geographies is aggregated from the population estimates for 2011 Data Zones.

Data zones are the small area geography used by the Scottish Government to allow statistics to be available across a number of policy areas. Data zones were initially set up to nest within council area boundaries and to have a population of between 500 and 1,000 household residents. As much as possible, data zones were set up to contain households with similar social characteristics and to take into consideration physical boundaries. More information on data zone geography can be found on the Scottish Government website. There are 6,976 data zones in Scotland.

Following the 2011 Census the Scottish Government completed a consultation on the redrawing of data zone boundary and finalised the new data zones. 2011 Data Zones were published at the end of 2014.

Intermediate zones are built up from data zones. Intermediate zones are the statistical small geographical areas designed to contain a population of between 2,500 and 6,000 household residents. There are 1,235 intermediate zones in Scotland. More information on intermediate geography can be found on the Scottish Government website.

For more information on population statistics, please see the NRS website here: https://www.nrscotland.gov.uk/statistics-and-data/statistics/statistics-by-theme/population/population-estimates/mid-year-population-estimates

Single year of age population estimates are available on the NRS website here: https://www.nrscotland.gov.uk/statistics-and-data/statistics/statistics-by-theme/population/population-estimates/2011-based-special-area-population-estimates/small-area-population-estimates

attributes.description:
Scottish Annual Business Survey 2017 (June 2019 release)- filtered for Renfrewshire.

Scottish Annual Business Statistics (SABS), which is largely sourced to the Annual Business Survey, provides data mainly on the Production (including Manufacturing), Construction and Service Sectors in Scotland. The main sectors not covered are the financial sector & parts of agriculture and the public sector. Data are classified according to industry group and geographical area. All figures are at current prices.

Variables include employment, employees, turnover, purchases of goods & services, approximate gross value added (GVA), gross wages & salaries, labour costs, total output and number of business units. GVA per head, gross wages & salaries per head and labour costs per head are also available.

attributes.description:
Detailed statistics on what mode of transport people usually use to get to work and education, as well as the percentage of total journeys which people make for a given purpose and children's mode of travel to school (from the Scottish Household Survey).

These estimates are from the Scottish Household Survey Travel Diary, which asks adult respondents about all the journeys which they made the previous day, as well as information about the mode, purpose, duration and length of these journeys. The proportion of people who travel to work by public or active travel is a National Indicator in the Scotland Performs framework.

SHS estimates are National Statistics and provide figures which are representative of households and individuals in Scotland annually. The SHS has an annual sample size of around 10,000 individuals and, since 2012, has operated with a fully unclustered sample design.

b) the geographical basis is the usual one for National Records of Scotland (NRS) statistics of births, which is births registered in Scotland to mothers who lived in the specified council area plus any births to mothers from outwith Scotland which occurred in the specified council area.

attributes.description:
The Renfrewshire Core Path Plan 2022 outlines the network of key access routes across Renfrewshire. The network of Core Paths identified in the Plan reflect key routes which aim to

Connect communities, settlements and places of interest;

Provide opportunities for active travel, particularly to schools and places of work;

Connect people with nature, areas of greenspace and the wider countryside; and

Promote and encourage healthy lifestyles.

This is the second Core Paths Plan for Renfrewshire and replaces the Core Paths Plan adopted in 2009.

The network provides a series of routes for people of all abilities. Not every route is suitable for everyone and the Plan provides information which helps to inform path users on the characteristics of each route.

The plan reflects the requirements of the Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003 in providing an up to date network of core routes which reflect current circumstances.

The group will use the funding to draught-proof their clubhouse so that it can operate as a comfortable and sustainable community venue.
The project will provide valuable support for breastfeeding mothers struggling to cope by recruiting and training locally based volunteer/mentors who can offer advice.
This charity will provide opportunities for members to engage in a programme of sporting activity including special residential weekends for their junior and company sections.
This charity will purchase equipment that will allow the group to distribute talking newspapers to service users on USB flash drives rather than on CDs.
This charity will use funding for the business planning for a new community performing arts theatre and performance academy.
This charity will use funding to modernise their website and distribute other materials aimed at promoting local support for the creation of national parks.
This charity will use funding to operate a community café for people at risk of isolation.
This charity will use the funding to offer water and outdoor sports to individuals diagnosed as having a learning disability by Renfrewshire Learning Disability Service (RLDS).

This charity work in partnership with Police Scotland to raise awareness of disability hate crime. The funding will be used to expand the ‘Keep Safe Ambassadors’ programme which trains young people who are aged over 14 years or age how to recognise and report hate crime within the community/school environment.

This group deliver SQA accredited ‘Comedy and Confidence’ workshops to young people referred to them by the Local Authority. These workshops develop confidence and resilience in the youngsters taking part. A recent success involved a group of young people presenting their experiences of care to their local Children’s Panel.

This group support women aged between 16 and 24 years of age who have experienced sexual abuse and violence. The funding will be used to help women take part in online and outdoor learning in a safe and care focused environment.
This group supports people with complex needs, the funding will give people they work with access to a range of outdoor activities at Castle Semple County Park.
This group will use funding to buy the equipment necessary to get their community radio station operating.
This group will use funding to celebrate 15 years of walking by organising a series of walking events throughout 2019. The walks will be accessible for people of all ages and abilities.
This group will use funding to make a local greenspace more appealing.
This group will use funding to organise a variety of community events and support sessions aimed at promoting integration and reducing isolation.
This group will use funding to provide creative interventions for people at risk of homelessness who will engage in small groups with community artists to learn creative and maintenance skills.
This group will use funding to send their members to Castle Semple to take part in the accessible sailing opportunities offered there.
This group will use funding to visit Castle Semple where they will take part in activities such as sailing, canoeing, photography walks and cycling.

This group will use the funding to continue to deliver Ready Steady Restore, a variety of workshops and play sessions for families in the Ferguslie Park and Shortroods areas of Paisley. In addition to fun and educational activities for children aged 0-8 the project will provide parents with a wide variety of recreational and development activities including peer-support listening sessions, family heritage workshops, and health and wellbeing workshops.

This group will use the funding to deliver a 13 day multi-cultural, multi-art festival in the semi-rural village of Lochwinnoch. The project is run by local volunteers of all ages, and will engage with other organisations and services in the village.
This group will use the funding to deliver one to one sessions and group workshops at schools in Renfrewshire focussing on improving mental health. They will also upgrade their website.

This group will use the funding to enable residents of the group’s care homes, who are all older or disabled ex service personnel, to undertake a programme of outdoor activities at the Castle Semple Centre.
This group will use the funding to offer cycling events to everyone within the community of Mary Russell.
This group will use the funding to provide a communication café for Black and Minority Ethnic women.

This group will use the funding to provide wheelchairs and scooters, free of charge, to support community members with mobility needs when they visit Paisley town centre. The group will also offer longer term hire for users going on holiday.

This group will use the funding to renovate the toilet facilities of their Carrick Centre building in Houston which is used as a base by a number of community groups. The new facilities will enable the group to retain and attract visitors to the centre.

This group, based in Paisley, will deliver a programme of arts activities, such as drama, dance, visual art, sewing, and film, for the residents of Montrose Care Home. The activities will also involve local schools.
This group, based in Renfrewshire, will purchase and install a modern sound system to help the school reach out and connect with their community through music and celebrations.
This Linwood based school will install a trim trail in their school grounds in order to promote active play amongst pupils and local children.
This local authority will run Coder-Dojo coding sessions for young people aged 8-18 years of age in partnership with Paisley YMCA. Sessions will be held in libraries in Linwood and Renfrew.

This organisation operates UK wide to provide support to families with a child affected by the life limiting conditions of Edward’s or Patau’s syndrome. The group will host a networking day which will give families affected by the condition in Scotland the chance to meet one another and develop supportive relationships.
This organisation will deliver intensive snow sports and life skills training for young people living in areas of high deprivation.
This organisation will use the funding to run a programme of water sports activities  for people with spinal injuries.

This school will use the funding to provide sports coaching for pupils with additional support needs. Activities will take place over a total of 35 days and will include sailing, canoeing, powerboating and cycling.

The trust (Linwood Community Development Trust) will use the funding to provide a continuation of their existing social and community activities, creating new opportunities to build peoples' skills and confidence. The programme of activities will be delivered through workshops and courses, to create learning opportunities for local groups. They will also continue to work with local schools to provide environmental projects and local planning events.

This centre provides a range of services and activities benefiting the local community. The funding will be used to continue delivering the Youth Club as well as funding sessional staff costs, art supplies and sports equipment.

This dance company works with disabled and non-disabled artists. The funding will be used to run dance and music based sessions for young people in targeted areas across Scotland.
This group provide care for ex service men and women. They will use the funding for a programme of outdoor recreational activities.

This group provide caring services to children and young people living in the Ferguslie Park area of Paisley before school, after school and during school holidays. The group will use the funding for camping equipment and arts materials.

This group support the work of Rockstar Cheer and Dance and Gymnastics, a competitive and recreational club for children and young people. The funding will enable the group to develop the clubs capacity to deliver gymnastics training.

This group will provide a confidential one to one outreach support service for the families of people affected by addiction . The project will benefit people from Indian, Pakistani and Bangladeshi communities living in Glasgow who will be supported by 30 volunteers.
This group will use the funding for coaching costs, equipment and venue hire so that they can run cricket sessions and activity days for people of all ages.
This group will use the funding for venue hire and promotional materials for their Friday evening indoor bowling club in order to encourage new membership and get elderly people to be more active.
This group will use the funding to develop their activities and hold two competitions.
This group will use the funding to produce three information workbooks and playing cards for young people affected by Huntington’s Disease to use.
This group will use the funding to run a basketball tournament for 200 people in teams in several categories; men over 50, men over 60 and women over 45.

This group works with adults with mental health problems and organise tutored drumming sessions as a form of therapy and as a social activity. They will use the funding for drumming sessions, community evening workshops, community outreach sessions, to publicise their services, a camcorder to record sessions and disseminate learning, and training.
This organisation provides recreational, sports and family support opportunities in the Renfrew area. The group will use the funding for a project to promote podiatry, self care and health.
This organisation will deliver opera sessions, performances and interactive workshops for the community.

This organisation will develop their garden area for families who use their service. It will provide a space for growing plants, a space for bikes and pedal cars, a bird feeding area, and a playhouse.

This organisation will establish a network for African people living in Glasgow with the aim of addressing loneliness and isolation. They will recruit and train volunteers to build the network through a range of activities.
This school will use the funding for a project about the honey bee.

attributes.searchDescription: A layer showing the location of large scale indoor venues in Paisley.

values.value: Methodist Central Halls regularly host cultural events.
Paisley 2021 Stadium is the home of St Mirren Football Club. The stadium has all of the facilities necessary to host and enjoy an event accommodating several thousand people.
Paisley Abbey provides a stunning backdrop and acoustic experience for musical performances.

Paisley Arts Centre is based in The Old Kirk in the heart of the town. It has been operating in its current form since 1987 and is one of Scotland?s best touring theatre, music, dance and comedy venues.
Paisley Museum and Art Gallery, in addition to the display of the permanent collections, incorporates three gallery spaces and a lecture theatre used for local organisations, talks and workshops.
Paisley Town Hall regularly hosts high-profile events including the Scottish Music Industry Association?s Scottish Album of the Year Award (2016 and 2017).
St Matthew?s Church regularly hosts concerts and a range of volunteer organisations working in the areas of alcohol and drug abuse.
The Brough Hall is located within a recently-redeveloped area of the University on Paisley High Street. The Brough Hall has cinema-quality projection and sound systems.
The Lagoon Arena is an accessible venue in the town centre with facilities that include a 1,500 capacity, live-broadcast equipped arena, including tiered seating.

The UWS Paisley Campus Student Union bars and venues are layered over three floors in Paisley Town Centre and feature large, accessible, flexible venues with high-spec equipment to support regular club nights, gigs, exhibitions and conferences.
The Wynd Centre is a church converted into a community centre with auditorium. It houses numerous groups and organisations in attached buildings.
Thomas Coats Memorial Church provides an incredible acoustic setting for music and events, including university graduation ceremonies.
Trinity Church regularly hosts cultural events.
